{"id":"2011.07841","submitter":"Antoine Riaud","authors":"Antoine Riaud, Qing Wang, Zhixiong Gong, Michael Baudoin, Jia Zhou","title":"Acoustic radiation force on small spheres due to transient acoustic\n  fields","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Applied 15, 044034 (2021)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevApplied.15.044034","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Acoustic radiation force is a net force experienced by an object under the\naction of an acoustic wave. Most theoretical models require the acoustic wave\nto be periodic, if not purely monofrequency, and are therefore irrelevant for\nthe study of acoustic radiation force due to acoustic pulses. Here, we\nintroduce the concept of finite-duration pulses, which is the most general\ncondition to derive the acoustic radiation force. In the case of small spheres,\nwe extend the Gor'kov to formula to unsteady acoustic fields such as traveling\npulses and interfering wave packets. In the latter case, our study suggests\nthat the concept of acoustic contrast is also relevant to express the acoustic\nradiation force. For negative acoustic contrast particles, the acoustic\ntrapping region narrows with shorter pulses, whereas positive contrast\nparticles (such as biological cells) can fall in secondary traps when the pulse\nwidth deviates from an optimal value. This theoretical insight may help to\nimprove the selectivity of pulsed acoustic tweezers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 16 Nov 2020 10:29:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-04-28"}
